      • addEncodedField

        public void addEncodedField(int tag,
                            String value)
                     throws BadDataExceptionWithCode
        Description copied from interface: IFIXMessageSpecifics
        Adds an encoded field preceded by its associated length field.

        This is a utility method. It does nothing that you could not do yourself using the basic methods. The advantage of using this method is that it reduces the risk of mistakes.

        This method does the following:

        • Confirms that tag is for an encoded field
        • Gets length field tag associated with the encoded field tag
        • Confirms that messageEncoded has been set for this message
        • Creates encoded field object from tag and value
        • Create the associated length field object set to appropriate length
        • Associates length field with encoded field
        • Adds length field to message's fields, immediately followed by encoded field

        Valid encoding must be set on this message or it will throw exception.

        Specified by:
        addEncodedField in interface IFIXMessageSpecifics
        Parameters:
        tag - Tag of field to be added
        value - Value of field to be added
        Throws:
        BadDataExceptionWithCode - if tag is not an encoded field or if message encoding has not been set

      • setUseExactFixDictionary

        public void setUseExactFixDictionary(boolean useExactFixDictionary)
        Description copied from interface: IFIXMessageSpecifics
        Set attribute to control whether session dictionary should be used when importing raw FIX bytes. By default the session will use the dictionary of the latest version of FIX when importing raw FIX bytes. This allows users to use fields from later versions of FIX in sessions configured to use earlier FIX versions. Set this value to true if you would like to use the dictionary of the FIX version of this session. You might need to do this if you use custom fields in your messages that are defined differently by a later version of the FIX protocol.
        Specified by:
        setUseExactFixDictionary in interface IFIXMessageSpecifics
        Parameters:
        useExactFixDictionary - true or false; default is false

      • iterator

        public ListIterator<ITagValue> iterator()
        Description copied from interface: ITagValueIterableFromTag
        Create an iterator over a collection of ITagValues.

        The following methods are not supported by the returned iterator:

        • java.util.ListIterator#remove()
        • java.util.ListIterator#add()
        • java.util.ListIterator#set()

        Calling any of them results in an UnsupportedOperationException.

        This method guarantees that a new iterator instance is returned with each call.

        The ITagValue objects returned are references to the underlying data, however, there are no guarantees regarding whether objects are created or not. Changing the values of these objects changes the underlying data. To avoid this behaviour you can use ITagValue.copyFrom(ITagValue) to copy the returned value before modifying it. If you intend on storing the returned ITagValue then copying it first is highly recommended.

      • bind

        public ListIterator<ITagValue> bind(ListIterator<ITagValue> iterator,
                                    ITagValue buffer)
        Description copied from interface: ITagValueIteratorBindable
        Bind an iterator to a collection of ITagValues.

        This method binds the specified iterator to the collection of ITagValues and resets it to the start so that iteration is over the complete collection. If an attempt is made to pass an incompatible iterator type a ClassCastException is thrown. It is possible to check beforehand using the IBindable.isBindable(Object) method.

        The caller may specify the return value buffer. This is like to be very efficient and is guaranteed not to involve object creation. However, modifying the ITagValue entry during iteration has no effect.

        If no return value buffer is specified then modifying the ITagValue entry modifies the underlying data, however, there are no guarantees about object creation.
